This Mongolian BBQ has been around since the 70s. I used to own the camera shop that was next door to the restaurant. Would go in there at least two or three times a week for lunch or dinner. I love the food though I do wish the selection of vegetables was more. We moved our location of the camera shop and Mongolian BBQ eventually expanded out knock down the wall and double their size. <text>Let me start off by saying that the month of May was, essentially, hell for me and my car and this Big-O location and Gary, specifically, eased that a bit. I took my car in at the beginning of May to have the fuel pump replaced as my car wasn't starting and, having had a similar problem with a previous car, I knew the signs. However, after replacing the fuel pump, we were still having problems. The car was fine for a week and then, again, wouldn't start for anything. So I brought her back and Gary immediately apologized for us having to bring her back so soon after our previous visit. After that, it was two weeks of limbo as Gary and his team tried to figure out what was wrong with the car. Every time we thought we knew what it was, they'd fix it and then, after an hour or so of testing, it wouldn't start again despite having started just fine a minute or two previous. And every step of the way Gary kept me updated. He'd call me and let me know what they'd tried and what they thought it was. He was always upfront with me about whether it was worth it to continue to try to sort out the problem given that the car itself is older. He promised that the car itself was solid. This glitch was just that. A glitch. Finally, it all boiled down to the internal computer that needed to be replaced and when I heard that all I saw was dollar signs flashing in front of me. Instead, Gary quoted me a reasonable price and, with their financing option, I was able to afford to get the necessary work done. Now, my car, thus far, has been running beautifully and I couldn't be more thankful for Gary and his team for taking such good care of my car and of me. This was a stressful and anxiety inducing few weeks, but, thanks to Gary, I knew that we were in good hands. Thank you guys so much!<//text>< Pictures>

Not Just Oil & Tires:
Diagnostic, Shock & Strauts, Breaks...

When you first walk in you are very impressed by how clean the facility is.
I would highly recommend this Big O Tire to anyone.

The staff is very friendly and the service is very quick, the prices are very fair and competitive.

The waiting area is very comfortable with a large screen TV, free refrigerated bottled water and hot coffee.  There are two single-use coed restrooms which are kept very clean. The facility is handicap friendly and accessible.

Overall the experience is excellent, you will walk away very pleased and will no doubt be back.

They are located at the opposite corner of Social Security next to Dollar Tree and Goodwill in the quad by McDonald's and Pollo Loco. Plenty of parking all around.<//text>< Rate>

<user_name>John Adriatico< /user_name><time>1560587880650<//time><Rate>3<//Rate>< Text>
Took my car for an oil change and tire rotation special. I'm giving three stars because the oil change and rotation was fine and done correctly, but  they misdiagnosed a problem with my car after their inspection. The manager pointed out I had a problem with the brake rotors on my car wearing unevenly, which to be fair, he did show me in person and there was a genuine problem with the brakes. However, he told me it would be fixed with a brake fluid flush and a rotor/pad change. I'm a shadetree mechanic who works on my car and I took my car to Big O for an oil change because I have nowhere to work at my residence. At this point, I asked him again if that would fix it and he said "yes." Uneven wear in brakes usually comes from a misaligned/damaged parking brake mechanism or a problem with the caliper pistons.

I took the car to my mechanic uncle and the caliper pistons were shot, which are the things that the fluid pushes to push the pads against the rotor. You cannot fix a broken disc brake caliper by only changing the brake pads and rotors then doing a fluid change. You either have to rebuild the caliper pistons or replace the caliper, and optimally it should be on both sides. I ended up replacing both calipers and rotors with my uncle, but if I would have followed their recommendations, I'd either have to pay more to replace the caliper or have an improper fix.<//Text>

<gmap_id>0x80d953570de48611:0x45ee66ba3e9ae298<//gmap_id>< Text>
Negligent staff and doctors. Don't bring your cat here if you want them to be competently examined.

My partner and I took our newly adopted kitten here in December to be checked out because we wanted her to be all cleared by a vet before letting her roam our apartment and introducing her to our older cat; she also had plastic non-dissolvable stitches that the shelter told us had to be removed. Banfield kept our kitten for 8hours. In that time, they only called us once or twice to tell is that she would be done "soon". One of those times the Vet (Dr. Friske) called and told us that she was having trouble removing the stitches and that we should just let them dissolve. We had to point out to the vet that they were plastic ones that would never dissolve. It was disappointing that the vet couldn't even tell.

After 8hours, we finally got our kitten back and thought she was all cleared after being tested and checked by the vet. We were wrong; that same night we noticed a round lesion on her leg that some googling quickly diagnosed as ringworm. We called the vet first thing in the morning asking them to confirm it was ringworm so that we could get her started on treatment. They made us pay the $64 general office visit fee even though we were there less than 24hours ago. They made us pay that fee even though this was something that absolutely should have been noticed in the 8 hours she was there the day prior. What could possibly justify keeping a cat for 8 hours and not noticing ringworm? The worst part wasn't even that we had to spend more money, it was the fact that we had so much anxiety and stress worrying that our older cat had also been exposed to ringworm because we had taken the vet visit as a green light for letting our kitten explore our apartment.

We have since switched vets over to West Coast Animal Hospital and are much happier with the level of attention and care that their office provided.</Text>

<Review>This was the first time I've ever visited a Banfield facility. It's only a block away from where I live, so it seemed convenient when my cat developed problems with his ears. I was able to get an appointment the same day, which was good. The doctor was very polite, but most of the exam and follow up were performed by the vet tech. I was charged $46 for a 7.5ml bottle of ear drops. and $37 for an ear flush liquid. When I got home, I discovered I could have purchased the $46 item for $11.75 at PetSmart. Let me start of by saying... My heart is shattered. It took me this long, exactly 4 months later, to want to post a review.
From November 2016 til March 2018 Banfield worked with us to attempt to figure out what was wrong with our pup.
She was a incredibly small Siberian Husky.
She had vomiting issues.

I was going to share her story, but it's too long for the reviews so to break it down.

Banfield did everything they could for Aurora. We spent $$$. We went into debt. From Nov 2016 to March 2018 banfield stood by us and tried to help find the cause of Auroras vomiting. Feb 2018 we could finally afford more so we did xray, and she needed intestine surgery.
We did it but Aurora decided after surgery and being home, she had to eat a bag as a midnight snack... I had only fallen asleep for an hour.... an hour I'll now always regret. She vomited it up but I guess not before it possibly ruined her stitches. She had not ate things like this before. Just food. I had no way of knowing she would.... (it was a bag of clothes... no good scents even in it... )
We had just used ALL the income we could. (Care credit, Income tax, and even tried a GoFundMe that failed.)
March 11th Aurora was seizing and couldn't stand. We took her in and the vet said it would cost lots of money with no real idea if it'll save her or the other option.... She was already showing signs of neurological disorder. She looked tired, weak... she looked done. You could tell in her eyes she was done.
I have a video of her licking my tears away as if to say it's okay.
I tried so hard to save her like she once saved me.
When she came into my life, she was becoming my emotional support animal. She saved me from depression after a miscarriage. She then gave me the strength to move across country, away from family, and she was there when I brought our son home after a successful pregnancy. She was my life support. My child. My best friend.

Theres so many pieces of this story I had to chop out because of it being too long. But please know I tried everything. Banfield did amazing. Every doctor and assistant showed Aurora so much love. The day Aurora left us, it felt like everyone there felt my pain. Kelsey, I believe, took her pawprints for me when I brought back an inkpad. Kelsey doesn't realize how much that means to me because now I permanently have Auroras print on my body, just as it is in my heart.
Banfield was like family and sometimes I think of stopping by there but I imagine they would think I'm odd, lol....

I've had a rough time coping with the loss of her.
I will ALWAYS blame myself for Aurora's passing.
Aurora would of been 2 June 14th this year. üíî

Thank you so much Banfield dr. and assistants. You tried everything. If I had just been a little richer, maybe we could of truly fixed her. Or maybe if I hadn't fallen asleep, the surgery would of been enough....

I'm still thankful for you all. Seriously so much. I can't say it enough.

**The pictures are the tattoo I got for her after she was gone.
And her with my son. She passed just as he was becoming mobile. If she was here now. She would LOVE having him chase her around. I wish they could of grown together like I envisioned..</review>

<text>My wife and I had recently rescued an 8 week old puppy and everything was going well. About a week later, he wasn't acting right. He was very lethargic, slept for an extended amount of time, and started whining profusely. After some thought about where to go, I took him to Banfield to get some help. My experience started out well.
It was a Sunday around 3 pm and Banfield had a skeleton staff working. The gentleman whom I started out with was alright. He wasn't very pleasant, but he was very knowledgeable. I was a bit on edge being a first time adopter, and to his benefit, he answered most of my questions. Then his shift apparently ended, and that's when things changed.
The lady that took over, Dr. Friske, started recommending tests to run. I ran them all. Blood, fecal matter, etc. It ended up costing $680. I just wanted to find out what was wrong with my dog.  By this time, my dog had vomited a few times and was swaying, so I was getting really nervous.
She had taken my dog to the back room and I hadn't seem him in over an hour. Another appointment showed up, so Dr. Friske came from the back saw us waiting, and went into another room to help the other patients, purposely avoiding us. We had been there for almost 3 hours at this point. Another 30 minutes later, she came out and walked towards us to tell us what was going on.
She let us know that all of the tests came back normal. Dr. Friske let us know that since everything was 'normal', she assumed he had distemper, which is a very serious disease. Even after we explained that he had had his distemper vaccination, she still believed that it had to have been passed through the mother.  There was no other options given to us. She talked about long term care and that he was going to have seizures for the rest of his life. We were crying in the waiting room. She handed us brochures on care management and walked away.
Another gentleman, that worked there, approached us and asked if we had any questions. He had mentioned that buying bells for our dog would be something we should do so that we could hear when he was having seizures. So there we were, in this waiting room with a 9 week old puppy that we were told is going to suffer immensely and have to be quarantined for the whole of his life. She had encouraged us to take the distemper test for an additional $400. We couldn't financially do it at the time, so we paid the $680 over 3 different cards and left.
We contacted the rescue where we got him and they called us the next day with some options. Since he had 2 rounds of vaccines (distemper included) the head of medical doubted he had distemper. No other dogs in the liter had it either. He recommended another vet to go to and the rescue offered to pay for the requisite tests to rule out distemper.
The second vet gave us 5 different possible causes with distemper being a very slim option.  After the tests came back negative for distemper, we came to the conclusion that he had eaten something that caused his symptoms. He has shown no other symptoms or have we had any other issues. He is now 13 weeks old and is super healthy.
Needless to say we will never step foot in Banfield again, in any location or any state. We feel like they took advantage of us being new to animal ownership and were very unprofessional in their approach. I would recommend you go to any other vet, just as long as you don't go here.<//text>< Resp>
None< /Resp>

<review>I've been taking my cat here and now my new dog, and was usually satisfied enough. I've always disliked the upselling - some vets are more aggressive than others - but brushed it off. Recently, I took my dog in for a lump on her head. The vet prodded the lump and said she had "no idea" what it could be, which surprised me. No idea? No thought at all of what it might be? I asked if it could be just from her hitting her head, but the vet said she'd never seen anything like it, but that they could take a sample of the cells for testing. I decided instead to go home and see if it got better on it's own, but the next day it was even bigger (maybe from all the poking and pressing on it), so I got scared and brought her back. When I picked her up, I was shocked to discover the charges totaled $324 - I paid $238 due to the "wellness" plan. This included some anti inflammatories, the procedure, the office visit, the lab work, and a $136 charge for "analysis and interpretation". Usually I ask about the charges ahead of time, since Banfield likes to add on extras without discussing them, but this time I was distraught and didn't do that. It's still annoying and frustrating that they don't go over the charges themselves. Three days later I was getting antsy about what the results were, so I looked up the lab it was sent to and discovered that this test sends results back in 1-3 days, not the 3-5 days quoted so I called. They had gotten the results back the next day, although no one bothered to call me. The vet who looked at my pup wasn't there, but another one looked at the results for a minute and said it's probably nothing to worry about. No explanation of what it could be. No analyzing the history or any notes made from the visit.

I decided I'm not going here ever again after my plan runs out. I wouldn't say that Banfield Pet Hospital is evil or negligent, they're more lackadaisical. If they're not pushing for procedures/services you don't really need, they're just ok. They don't really followup or seem very concerned about your pet. There's other, more highly recommended vets in the area, so it's not like this is the only place to go. I would give them three stars for my "meh" rating, but I find it outrageous that they charge $136 to look at some bloodwork, especially when I discovered this is the highest amount out of other vets in the area, so one star it is.

Update:
I talked with the business owner over this situation, and she agreed that I should have been notified of all charges before paying. She said she'd look into this and see if I could get a refund - but she never got back to me.

I met someone at the dog park who was also surprised at extra charges at Banfield, so this seems to be a habit for them. It's too late for me, but heres a tip: file a chargeback with your credit card to get your money back (just be sure to do it within 90 days). You shouldn't have to pay for these surprise charges. This is very unethical and against the terms with the credit card processing. I now go to Bodhi Animal Hospital in North Park, and they review charges BEFORE they render care, so I'm fully informed.< /review><pics>None< /pics>< Resp>
None< /Resp>

<Review>I've been taking my baby kitten here since we got him and until this visit I was very happy with all the staff and the vets, we signed up for the most expensive kitten wellness plan and figured that would have us covered.

Today we brought our kitten in because he had been acting lethargic and weak and we were incredibly worried about him. The vet was lovely as usual and very good with our kitten and said it could be an infection or a string stuck in his bowels (without any indigestion, diarrhea, vomiting, lack of appetite or stomach pain?) and the vet tech preceded to try to convince us to get $160 worth of blood work and also a $250 x ray for something he clearly didn't have.

We decided to get him the antibiotics they recommended and see if they helped before dropping $200 on blood work. The rest of our visit she proceeded to shame us and make us feel guilty for waiting to do the blood work. She told the other employee that we weren't getting the recommended tests quite loudly in the waiting area.

I get the feeling that they scare most people into dropping thousands of dollars into tests before even getting to the treatment. I've never experienced these hard selling tactics at a vet before(maybe I've just had good luck before this) and I think preying on people's devoted love for their pets is disturbing and vile.<//Review>< Pics>

< Review>
I usually go later, early afternoon, and lines going in are non-existent. Lines going out are slower, 5-10 minutes or more.

I like the basic garbage area, it's all concrete, covered building, easy in and out.

The yard waste area is round the corner of concrete area. Dirtier, I even got an item in my tire, ending getting a flat. No biggie though.

All and all, great place.</Review>

<username>Ken Yi</username><Gmap_id>0x80c2d0b1f0f5b3d3:0x82f32f5eabc29a09<//Gmap_id>< review>
This is good news if you live far 15 plus miles away and you want a courtesy shuttle ride.  The driver tells me they drive 15 to 30 miles away for shuttle service.  They only have 1 shuttle and when they drive farthest distance first, those living close will be held hostage in the car for 40 to 50 minutes in my case.  Apparently they have rules for female customers to be dropped off first if only guys are in the car.  That is a great policy.  But I was the 2nd person dropped off and 50+ minute drive for my 3 miles away drop off seems too much.  If they want to do these long distance drop off use the back up car.  They must have a back up shuttle right?  This doesn't make sense to hold people hostage for this long.  Mixed thoughts on this.  Service can be better!

BTW.  Car service itself was good.< /review>

<UserId.>114660084880160814911<//UserId.><rate>1</rate>< text>
Updated: 2019 - Vehicle Repainted Twice
As friendly as the representatives were at the time I purchased the vehicle, I had 2 significant problems that were dismissed.
1. Name of account holder was incorrect, I contacted the dealership dozens of times by phone and email and in person requesting a correction. Was told several times the request was being processed and to check back within 3-5 days. Unfortunately they never corrected the problem.
2. The paint on my vehicle began to oxidize after 2 years. Fortunately this was not an isolated case and there was a recall for oxidized paint on a wide range of Honda models. I spent 2 years contacting this dealership dozens of times, sent photographs and spoke to several managers. When they finally painted the vehicle, it took over 1 month and I was not provided with a rental car. There were a lot of problems, paint on windows, broken interior door handles, cracked seals. The greatest issue was the recall didn't cover re-painting the entire vehicle. I spent a month trying to get the issues corrected and ended up giving up.
- - - - - -
2 years after the Honda Civic was repainted, the paint on the hood began to peel. Paint on the roof began to oxidize. Returned the vehicle to be painted once again. This time the vehicle was returned with new scratches and dents. After numerous calls and emails to the rep and the service center throughout the span of 3 months.. no response. I eventually gave up.</text>

<user_id>101124834554713877701<//user_id><Pics>None</Pics><rating>2< /rating>< Review>
Hello,

Out of nowhere I get a call to let me know there's a recall for the airbags on my vehicle which I found good as I feel my vehicle is old but made me feel that Honda cares for their vehicles and is responsible.
I scheduled an appointment for 7/6719, a Saturday morning at 7AM.
I received two calls for reminder of my appointment.
I'm thinking everything is being handled very professional, to a point that would make me feel my next new car should be a Honda as they do seem to care about safety, are professionals, and attentive.
I got there at 6:45AM only to find two vehicles blocking the Service entry, a White GMC and a Black Honda Accord.
My wife had to be at work at 8AM and as more cars were gathering around and behind me which I knew weren't going to respect the fact that I got there first and as soon as any of the two vehicles blocking the entrance were moved either of the vehicles around me were gonna go in before me and they DID, I automatically knew things were going South.
The Vehicles blocking the entrance were moved at 7:09 exactly, I called more than three times and the phone only rang with no answer as I waited there till they opened at 7:09AM.
1. My appointment at 7:00AM was not respected.
2. The oriental gentleman had excellent customer service but misspelled my first name, I crossed it out and corrected it in front of him.
3. The shuttle service starts at 8:00AM and I had to call and use Lyft for a ride home, I feel Shuttle service should begin once open, very inconvenient.
4. My wife was late to work for waiting on me, all to Service Department opening late and vehicles going in ahead of me because when vehicles at entrance were moved, it granted them access to go in first even though I got there first.
5.  I pick up my Car and again, the guy was great but when I look at the Invoice, my name was mispelled again even though he saw me crossing and correcting it the first time and even talked about how it's spelled differently.

Everything started good but I ended very disappointed.

It was just too good to be true.

Best regards,

Jhonattan Vazquez</Review>

< review>
times: 7-9 am
Appointmens: online and over the phone, very easy and they do the standard 24 hr pre appointment reminder
instruction: when u arrive get off ur car and go look for ur technician its a mad house when u get there, if u cant get off ur car roll ur window down and call for ur rep. they will walk fown the aisle of cars to check people in but im too impatient.

customer service: seen 3 different reps and they are consistent, good friendly service.
cost: use coupons from their site, i normally go for the standard oil tire rotation package.

waiting area: small but clean, not too many power outlets, and the wifi is free just look for their sign that has the password.

<user_id>114597725927733579202< /user_id>< user_name>
Nancy Pistole< /user_name>
<Date>1531173363585</Date>< Rate>
1</Rate>
< text>
I was looking for a '13 Honda Fit. My first choice was to buy from a private party, but El Monte Honda advertised a car that was what I was looking for, so I did my research beforehand (luckily) and went there. El Monte Honda lived down to (almost) every expectation I had of a dealership.

I called ahead of time to make sure that the car would be available for a test drive. The sales person on the phone said that the car had Bluetooth and a back-up camera. The ad did not say the car had those features (I didn't want those features), and when I saw the car, it did not have Bluetooth or a backup camera.

James showed me the car--it seemed to be just what I was looking for. We looked it over--the license plate was falling off, only held on by one sheet metal screw. James said he would get the service department to fix it, so my friend (a mechanic) said it should be fastened with bolts. The service department fixed it with two sheet metal screws, so the next day my friend retapped the upper holes (that had been damaged) and fastened the license plate with bolts (the way it should be). I'm wary to trust the service department to do any maintenance on my car, and it certainly makes me wonder if they really did the 182-point inspection they were supposed to do for a Certified Pre-Owned car.

James was enthusiastic, but didn't know the car very well. He couldn't figure out how to open the door to get to the gas cap. When my friend (a mechanic) commented that the engine had a timing chain, James said it actually had a 'wet belt' (there isn't such a thing!). He also said that there was a seven-year powertrain warranty that started when I bought the car (not true, it starts from the original in-service date). While I was standing beside the Fit, another sales person said that the car came with three months of free XM radio (not on a Fit). Another sales person said the seat adjusted up and down (not on a Fit). Do any sales people know about the cars they are selling?

The sticker price on the window was over $1000 more than their internet ad that I brought with me. When I showed them the ad, they honored the lower price without any problem. However, when they printed out the first invoice, they tried to add $995 for a security system (I read in previous reviews that this tactic was common). I said I didn't want the security system, so they redid the invoice without the added charge (that took some time). I said I was paying cash, but they said they still had to do a credit check because it was over $10,000. I had to wait for over an hour for them to get an okay. (I have good credit, but it shouldn't mattered anyway with cash.)

The finance guy, Sergio, seemed to know what he was doing, and the actual financial transaction went quickly. I didn't have exact change, and Sergio didn't have change, so he said that he would send me a refund check for the overpayment. After several weeks, I didn't receive a check, so I called him up and he said he would send it right out. I finally got the check a week later.

The car was supposed to come with a manual (according to Certified Pre-Owned specs), but the dealership didn't have one. James said he would try to find one to send to me. A few weeks later I called about it, and they said they had just received one, but I needed to come in to pick it up (the dealership is a long ways away). After being transferred to several people, I talked to the parts guy who said he would mail it to me. That saved me an extra trip.

In conclusion, if you are going to this dealership, know what you want and do your homework beforehand. Be prepared that everyone there will tell you what you want to hear whether or not it is true.</text>

<Review>Updated review on 05/29/18.

TL;DR:
Get profiled, then get told you won't get help unless you commit to buying.

The long version:
I decided to rewrite this review for clarity (ha! pun intended - it'll make sense later). On Sunday 05/27/18 I was looking into possibly buying a new car and my wife and I chose El Monte Honda due to the 490+ reviews on Google with an average rating of 4.5 over Downey Honda which at the time of writing had 350+ reviews with an average rating of 4.0. Both dealerships with around the same distance from where I live so we went to the one with the higher rating.

Strike one.

We arrived at the lot and after parking were greeted by James - who was pleasant and asked the reason for our visit today. I let him know that we were interested in either the Clarity PHEV (see, the pun above makes sense now) or the Accord and he let me know that although he works with used vehicles - he would find another associate to assist me. We lingered around the lobby for a few minutes and we were next approached by an Asian female associate who asked us directly in Mandarin what were wanted to do today. I was taken aback initially that 1) I never spoke in Mandarin to James and 2) why the associate and/or the dealership management assumed I would speak Mandarin. In that brief moment of shock I did respond to her in Mandarin (because yes, I do speak it) and repeated what I stated earlier to James. She told me to hold on and she will find someone to help me and as I turned around she repeated what I just said in Mandarin to the tall African American gentleman to her side who I'm assuming is her sales manager.

Strike two.

We linger around again for just a brief moment when an older Mandarin- speaking associate named Jeff approached and introduced himself to us. I responded to him in English as that's my preferred language of communication and asked if we could proceed with our interaction in English. Jeff let me know it was no problem and asked what we were interested in today. Once again I repeated what I told James and the Asian female associate. Upon hearing me say that I was unsure if I was ready to buy today - Jeff (albeit politely and in somewhat of an apologetic tone) stated that due to the fact that it's Memorial Day weekend and they are really busy, he'd be happy to quickly show me some cars but it would not be possible for me to test drive any cars since he wants to make sure that he is able to properly assist customers who have committed to buying.

Strike three.

He proceeded to walk us outside and pointed at the three Accords immediately outside the showroom door and said he didn't know where the Clarity PHEV was (it was outside on the opposite side of the showroom - we walked past it on the way in). I once again wanted to clarify (ha! pun intended again) that I heard him correctly that he did say that since we were not committed to buying today that he was not going to allow us to test drive any cars. He confirmed and I thanked him for his time and my wife and I decided to leave.

Successful business is built through customer relationships and rapport, and in my brief 15 minutes at this dealership, I did not feel that this issue was of paramount importance to the staff and management who would rather prioritize the sale.

We went straight to Downey Honda where I eventually purchased the brand new 2018 Honda Clarity PHEV pictured with my review.

As with all internet reviews, my experience could have been unique, but your mileage may vary.<//Review>< Date>

< Review>
(The two stars is for the salesmen that helped me out and for the most of the staff. The blank ones as well as only getting two stars is for the yo-yo financing, spot-delivery and the back and forth with the finance dept).

Came in after heading to three different dealers (Nissan, Toyota, Ford), hoping to get a car. Not the greatest credit in the world, but fair. They got me in a 2018 Honda Civic hatch. Awesome (spot-delivery). Then, we found out that I‚Äôm not approved (here is the back and forth with finance, no co-signer and etc...). Okay fine (three weeks of that). We unwind the car (here comes the yo-yo). Got a used 2015 Mitsubishi Outlander (nice car, starts up a little harsh but good, drives a little weird, but okay all good), Brent told me I had to (HAD TO) get a 2yr warranty or else they wouldn‚Äôt give me the car (because that‚Äôs how it‚Äôs structured in the lenders terms), asked why? Said the lender wants it that way (SantanderConsumer).Warranties are optional, but I guess it depends, but for the most part it‚Äôs almost always optional (dealer sells it to you). Verified with manager in the dealership it‚Äôs optional but depends on deal, but almost always optional. I also got stuck with one of the worst lenders you could think of (Santander is notorious for extremely high APR%, read the reviews. Some people don‚Äôt get out of their deals easily, some get stuck with more payments, payments don‚Äôt go through and etc), and I get popped with a 22% interest rate (yo-yo financing=you get a spot delivery, you take the car, couple days later you get a call and dealer tells you you need more money down or a co-signer and etc, you agree to turn it in, but then you sign a contract that is in more of the dealers favor for another car, but this time you‚Äôre financing it and your interest rate is sky high and you they start loan packing and etc). Luis and Bryan (salesman did their jobs good, mike the manager as well, pretty all salesman are cool), Brent is the one that hit me with ‚ÄúHAVE TO‚Äù warranty, Mario (finance has attitude, but he‚Äôs alright), Tony (attitude but he‚Äôs okay), Albert (manager, helped out with cancelling the 2015 outlander.

With all this being said, I loved the Civic, but couldn‚Äôt keep it, the Mitsubishi (loved it more because of space, but mechanically questionable because of the sounds coming from the engine), but what really screwed everything up was the Mitsubishi deal, and the lack of communication on the first purchase (Civic, I expected calls, nothing, I called the dealer more than they called me for sure, I wanted to solidify that deal, so I was pissed half the time). What drove it home was the bad deal in the end.

Overall great experience. I found a coupon online for a coolant flush and refill service that includes a leak test. My service consultant, Andika was very helpful. I explained to him that I was told from a different Honda dealership that my 2008 Civic Si had a leak in one of my coolant hoses but refused to tell me which one and recommended a complete rehose.. which has been a headache since I've babied this car. Andika stated that the leak could be seen while bleeding the coolant system. The service was estimated to be finished in about an hour or so. About 50 mins passed, Andika gave me a call to explain to me that the car is finishing up, and there are no visible leaks. He asked me to come to take a look at the car while it's still up. Upon arrival, he alongside the service mechanic Danny, used a flashlight to show me that there were no leaks. Then I was told that they'll finish up and will give me a call when it's fully done.

Once I received my car, I checked under the hood, and my coolant in the reservoir was lower than the minimum. I asked a worker there and they called the service mechanic Danny back. He explained that the coolant will come back once I started driving but if I felt more comfortable with it being topped off, he'll put some in. I then requested it to be topped off and he came back with coolant and put it in no problem.. after that he complimented my car and we were chatting about cars.. he gave me some advice on how to maintain my vehicle. He was probably the most informative service mechanic I have ever encountered at a Honda dealership.

I will definitely return to El Monte Honda for services. Very great experience on all parts of the service for a first time customer.< /Review>
